  "issue_number": 833,
  "issue_title": "Make the watchlist column sortable across tables",
  "issue_body": "## Summary\n\nThe \u2605 column shows up on a few tables \u2014 the Repositories list view (OSS and Issue Discovery), the Top Miners list, and the Watchlist Pull Requests tab. It holds the row-level watchlist star (add / remove from your watchlist). Right now the column header isn't clickable \u2014 clicking it does nothing \u2014 so there's no way to pull your starred rows to the top of the list.\n\nI'd like clicking the \u2605 header to sort the table by watchlist status, the same way every other column header does. First click puts watched rows at the top; a second click flips the order. Stars added or removed should re-sort the list right away.\n\n## Motivation\n\nWhen I scan one of these long tables, the rows I care about most are the ones I've already starred. To find them today I have to scroll, search by name, or jump over to the Watchlist page. The \u2605 column already tells me which rows are watched, so it feels natural that clicking its header would sort by it \u2014 that's how the other columns work.\n\nThis helps in a few everyday situations:\n\n- On the Repositories page (OSS or Issue Discovery), seeing where my tracked repos rank against the rest without leaving the leaderboard.\n- On Top Miners, surfacing the miners I follow alongside the full ranking.\n- On the Watchlist Pull Requests tab, grouping still-starred PRs above any I've since unstarred.\n\nThe watchlist data is already in local storage, the \u2605 column already exists on these tables, and the sort plumbing is already wired up for the other columns. This is mostly about plugging the \u2605 header into the same sort state so the click does what it visually promises.\n",
  "merged_at": "2026-04-30T01:50:43.000Z",
